to work at this stuff.

00:45:14.810 --> 00:45:18.290
So, Joe McCarthy,
backbencher, Wisconsin,

00:45:18.290 --> 00:45:20.060
not a particularly
interesting senator.

00:45:20.060 --> 00:45:24.320
He's looking for a
national issue in 1950.

00:45:24.320 --> 00:45:28.230
There were communists in
the government in the '40s,

00:45:28.230 --> 00:45:30.050
but Harry Truman got
rid of most of them.

00:45:30.050 --> 00:45:33.040
In a loyalty program, the
Civil Liberties folks hated

00:45:33.040 --> 00:45:35.460
but still got rid of them.

00:45:35.460 --> 00:45:38.550
McCarthy comes along, he's
soul-- Cohn later wrote--

00:45:38.550 --> 00:45:41.430
his lawyer later wrote that he
bought anti-communism the way

00:45:41.430 --> 00:45:44.120
other people might buy a car.

00:45:44.120 --> 00:45:46.750
It was an issue, it
was something to ride.

00:45:46.750 --> 00:45:49.080
Lincoln's birthday, Wheeling
West Virginia, he says,

00:45:49.080 --> 00:45:52.560
he has in his pocket a 205
communists, the number wandered

00:45:52.560 --> 00:45:55.900
down to 57, he never
really found any.

00:45:55.900 --> 00:45:57.780
Reign of terror of four years.

00:45:57.780 --> 00:46:02.430
Now, think about that, four
years from Lincoln's birthday,

00:46:02.430 --> 00:46:08.770
1950, February until late 1954.

00:46:08.770 --> 00:46:16.510
Parenthetically, as well, June
17th, 1972 to August 9th, 1974,

00:46:16.510 --> 00:46:19.180
people want these things
to move more quickly,

00:46:19.180 --> 00:46:22.630
but that's not the way
history actually unfolds.

00:46:22.630 --> 00:46:24.190
For almost 48 months,

00:46:24.190 --> 00:46:27.200
Joe McCarthy terrorized the
United States of America.

00:46:27.200 --> 00:46:31.050
And he did it through the
manipulation of the media

00:46:31.050 --> 00:46:34.110
through an appeal to
broad popular fear

00:46:34.110 --> 00:46:36.430
at a time of transition.

00:46:36.430 --> 00:46:44.290
He did it kind of promising
to make America unpinch again.

00:46:44.290 --> 00:46:48.280
He understood the means of
communication of his time.

00:46:48.280 --> 00:46:50.330
The afternoon papers
used to close at noon,

00:46:50.330 --> 00:46:52.680
so McCarthy would call
press conferences at 11:30

00:46:52.680 --> 00:46:55.210
in the morning and say
I am seeking a communist

00:46:55.210 --> 00:46:58.140
in Des Moines, headlines
all around the country.

00:46:58.140 --> 00:47:00.390
Senator seeks red in Des Moines.

00:47:00.390 --> 00:47:02.020
He did it 11:30 so they
couldn't have time--

00:47:02.020 --> 00:47:03.320
they didn't have time to check.

00:47:03.320 --> 00:47:05.740
Then he waited till 11:30 p.m.

00:47:05.740 --> 00:47:07.670
because the morning
papers closed at midnight.

00:47:07.670 --> 00:47:09.760
And he said, the read
in Des Moines is eluding

00:47:09.760 --> 00:47:11.790
but I'm redoubling my efforts,

00:47:11.790 --> 00:47:15.490
flashes across America,
redoubles efforts.

00:47:15.490 --> 00:47:17.410
Radio helped him.

00:47:17.410 --> 00:47:22.650
When he took to the stump
in Wheeling, in 1950,

00:47:22.650 --> 00:47:24.820
there were 3.1 million
televisions

00:47:24.820 --> 00:47:26.870
in American households.

00:47:26.870 --> 00:47:28.780
When he was censured in 1954,

00:47:28.780 --> 00:47:34.050
there were 30.6,
immense sea-change.

00:47:34.050 --> 00:47:38.670
And the good news about that, if
you believe that the truth will

00:47:38.670 --> 00:47:43.590
out and that leaders who are not
appealing to our better angels

00:47:43.590 --> 00:47:46.060
but are in fact dealing in
hope traffic, I mean traffic

00:47:46.060 --> 00:47:50.890
in fear is exposure killed him.

00:47:50.890 --> 00:47:52.420
People watched him long enough

00:47:52.420 --> 00:47:55.980
to think this is not
who we want to be.

00:47:55.980 --> 00:47:59.150
But let me tell you who you
definitely want to have been.

00:47:59.150 --> 00:48:01.590
And I thought about her
all morning and you want

00:48:01.590 --> 00:48:06.520
to be Margaret Chase Smith, the
Republican senator from Maine

00:48:06.520 --> 00:48:08.950
who within a month of the speech

00:48:08.950 --> 00:48:13.440
in Wheeling gave a speech called
the declaration of conscience

00:48:13.440 --> 00:48:17.290
in which she laid out the
exact case against McCarthy.

00:48:17.290 --> 00:48:19.440
I urge you to go read it.

00:48:19.440 --> 00:48:23.610
There was no further
intellectual or moral movement

00:48:23.610 --> 00:48:26.770
by 1954 when the
censure vote happened

00:48:26.770 --> 00:48:29.670
from what Senator
Smith laid out.

00:48:29.670 --> 00:48:32.470
McCarthy dismissed-- and
she only got six senators

00:48:32.470 --> 00:48:33.830
to sign it with her.

00:48:33.830 --> 00:48:38.120
McCarthy dismissed them as "Snow
White and the Six Dwarves".

00:48:38.120 --> 00:48:44.260
But here we are in
2018 talking about her.

00:48:44.260 --> 00:48:47.680
We're not talking about the
senators who took a dive

00:48:47.680 --> 00:48:52.330
or who wanted to wait to
see the next poll or wanted

00:48:52.330 --> 00:48:54.760
to wait it out a little bit.

00:48:54.760 --> 00:48:58.150
We're talking about the one who
stood and said this is wrong.

00:48:58.150 --> 00:49:00.890
And that's what we need more of.

00:49:00.890 --> 00:49:06.440
And whenever I talked to
folks who actually have power,

00:49:06.440 --> 00:49:12.150
one of the things I try to say
is what do you want us to think

00:49:12.150 --> 00:49:14.670
when we look at your
oil portrait?

00:49:14.670 --> 00:49:17.460
And it works because they
can't imagine a world

00:49:17.460 --> 00:49:21.410
where we're not gazing
adoringly at their oil portrait.

00:49:21.410 --> 00:49:24.050
So it's kind of a passive
aggressive thing, it works.

00:49:24.050 --> 00:49:28.190
And I was thinking
all morning, you know,

00:49:28.190 --> 00:49:29.710
I was sitting outside
the cathedral

00:49:29.710 --> 00:49:33.000
and all those senators
sitting there

00:49:33.000 --> 00:49:36.100
and what do they
think people are going

00:49:36.100 --> 00:49:39.410
to be saying about them?

00:49:39.410 --> 00:49:41.940
You're afraid of a guy
with a Twitter finger

00:49:41.940 --> 00:49:44.620
and a 36% approval rating?

00:49:45.910 --> 00:49:48.510
Yeah. Anyway--

00:49:48.510 --> 00:49:52.850
[ Applause ]

00:49:52.850 --> 00:49:57.170
So, you want to be
Margaret Chase Smith,

00:49:57.170 --> 00:49:59.070
you want to be Margaret
Chase Smith, and you want

00:49:59.070 --> 00:50:01.530
to urge people not to agree--

00:50:01.530 --> 00:50:04.930
we don't have to agree all
the time, we never have

00:50:04.930 --> 00:50:08.000
from loyalists versus
patriots to isolationist

00:50:08.000 --> 00:50:12.690
versus interventionists to
globalist versus protectionism,

00:50:12.690 --> 00:50:14.390
we're always going to fight.

00:50:14.390 --> 00:50:17.010
The country was built to fight.

00:50:17.010 --> 00:50:19.430
The country was built to have
guardrails so that we would

00:50:19.430 --> 00:50:23.160
at least stay basically
on the road.

00:50:23.160 --> 00:50:25.620
But here are a couple of
three characteristics given

00:50:25.620 --> 00:50:29.390
to you fast that I think
we need and I think

00:50:29.390 --> 00:50:35.400
that presidents need, and public
officials need in order to win

00:50:35.400 --> 00:50:37.390
that battle within the soul.

00:50:37.390 --> 00:50:39.300
The first is curiosity.

00:50:39.300 --> 00:50:40.600
Absolutely essential.

00:50:40.600 --> 00:50:43.380
The greatest eras, the
greatest presidents are ones

00:50:43.380 --> 00:50:45.080
who are intellectually curious.

00:50:45.080 --> 00:50:47.970
Thomas Jefferson was able to
write that sentence not simply

00:50:47.970 --> 00:50:50.980
because he was a rising
young politician of Virginia

00:50:50.980 --> 00:50:54.930
in the third week of June
1776, but because he was

00:50:54.930 --> 00:51:00.100
in a broad conversation with
the European enlightenment,

00:51:00.100 --> 00:51:01.400
the Scottish moral
enlightenment,

00:51:01.400 --> 00:51:04.910
the Scientific Revolution,
the Protestant Reformations,

00:51:04.910 --> 00:51:08.480
the introduction of Gutenberg,
an entire reorientation

00:51:08.480 --> 00:51:14.450
of the world from being seen
as being run by kings, popes,

00:51:14.450 --> 00:51:19.720
prelates, prince's, people who
either by an accident of birth

00:51:19.720 --> 00:51:25.020
or an incident of election were
given power over all of us,

00:51:25.020 --> 00:51:27.290
a vertical understanding.

00:51:27.290 --> 00:51:29.470
And what was happening with the
American Revolution is it was

00:51:29.470 --> 00:51:33.480
becoming more horizontal,
that we were all born

00:51:33.480 --> 00:51:36.010
with that capacity to
determine our own destinies

00:51:36.010 --> 00:51:39.130
and that it wouldn't
simply lie in the hands

00:51:39.130 --> 00:51:42.190
of a pope or of a prince.

00:51:42.190 --> 00:51:48.560
Jefferson was able to set that
in motion incomplete as it was

00:51:48.560 --> 00:51:52.370
because he was voraciously
curious about what was going

00:51:52.370 --> 00:51:53.800
on in the rest of the world.

00:51:53.800 --> 00:52:00.460
And I think that this-- the
baseline of citizenship always

00:52:00.460 --> 00:52:03.910
but particularly
today is realizing

00:52:03.910 --> 00:52:09.210
that the American Revolution
was the political manifestation

00:52:09.210 --> 00:52:14.380
of the idea that reason has
to have a chance in the arena

00:52:14.380 --> 00:52:18.700
against passion that
we've been given a brain,

00:52:18.700 --> 00:52:21.970
we've been given the capacity
to weigh different arguments

00:52:21.970 --> 00:52:23.900
and come to a reasoned
conclusion.

00:52:23.900 --> 00:52:30.500
And if we don't reflect and
use reason and if we fall prey

00:52:30.500 --> 00:52:35.930
to reflexive partisanship,
then we're not being true

00:52:35.930 --> 00:52:39.590
to the reality of
the revolution.

00:52:39.590 --> 00:52:41.740
Partisanship is fine.

00:52:41.740 --> 00:52:46.180
Partisanship is the air
we breathe, is the price

00:52:46.180 --> 00:52:49.440
of free government,
but we have to,

00:52:49.440 --> 00:52:52.980
we have to make it
reflective not reflexive,

00:52:52.980 --> 00:52:55.400
so curiosity is one.

00:52:55.400 --> 00:52:56.700
The second is humility.

00:52:56.700 --> 00:52:59.220
We've got to figure out
how to admit mistakes.

00:52:59.220 --> 00:53:01.470
We wouldn't be here if Jack
Kennedy hadn't been able

00:53:01.470 --> 00:53:04.110
to admit a mistake
from the Bay of Pigs

00:53:04.110 --> 00:53:06.200
to the Cuban Missile Crisis.

00:53:06.200 --> 00:53:08.730
Remember after the Bay of
Pigs in April of '61, he said,

00:53:08.730 --> 00:53:10.030
how could I have been so stupid?

00:53:10.030 --> 00:53:13.110
In a parliamentary system,
I would have resigned.

00:53:13.110 --> 00:53:16.230
He calls the last men on earth
before him he wished to appear

00:53:16.230 --> 00:53:19.490
in need of tutelage, and
that was Dwight Eisenhower,

00:53:19.490 --> 00:53:20.890
ask him to come to Camp David.

00:53:20.890 --> 00:53:23.750
Eisenhower says, you have
to have everybody in a room,

00:53:23.750 --> 00:53:26.790
you have to weigh the pros and
cons, you can't run these things

00:53:26.790 --> 00:53:28.570
out of your back pocket.

00:53:28.570 --> 00:53:31.980
Cut to October 1962,
casualty estimates

00:53:31.980 --> 00:53:35.810
of a possible hemispheric
exchange of nuclear weapons

00:53:35.810 --> 00:53:38.160
in the Cuban Missile
Crisis range between 70

00:53:38.160 --> 00:53:39.910
and a 100 million Americans.

00:53:39.910 --> 00:53:43.180
They could have gotten to
this city in 20 minutes.

00:53:43.180 --> 00:53:45.750
Many of the people in this
room would not have been here.

00:53:45.750 --> 00:53:49.260
The whole structure of
life might have ended

00:53:49.260 --> 00:53:51.570
if Kennedy had not had
the humility to admit

00:53:51.570 --> 00:53:53.940
that he made a mistake
and he needed to learn.

00:53:53.940 --> 00:53:56.480
One of the many tragedies
of Dallas is

00:53:56.480 --> 00:53:58.790
that Jack Kennedy is one
of the few presidents,

00:53:58.790 --> 00:54:02.630
Lincoln's another, who were
self-evidently learning

00:54:02.630 --> 00:54:04.070
as they held that office.

00:54:04.070 --> 00:54:06.270
It's so hard to learn
at that level.

00:54:06.270 --> 00:54:10.010
It just-- it-- the
pressures are such.

00:54:10.010 --> 00:54:14.990
But they were able to do it and
we are better off because of it.

00:54:14.990 --> 00:54:16.520
The last is empathy.

00:54:16.520 --> 00:54:18.160
And I want to leave
you with this.

00:54:18.160 --> 00:54:24.490
If I don't care about
you and if you don't

00:54:24.490 --> 00:54:28.270
at least nominally
care about me,

00:54:28.270 --> 00:54:32.330
democracy doesn't really work
because why should you pay taxes

00:54:32.330 --> 00:54:35.080
to help me and vice-versa

00:54:35.080 --> 00:54:38.200
if we don't have a
sense of sociability?

00:54:38.200 --> 00:54:41.040
But Gordon Wood, the great
historian, I know has been here,

00:54:41.040 --> 00:54:45.020
called sociability,
neighborliness,

00:54:45.020 --> 00:54:47.200
if we don't understand that
we're in this together,

00:54:47.200 --> 00:54:51.150
what Dr. King called a
mutual garment of destiny.

00:54:51.150 --> 00:54:52.450
That requires empathy.

00:54:52.450 --> 00:54:55.910
I don't have to love
you to death.

00:54:55.910 --> 00:54:58.850
We don't have to spend
a lot of time talking.

00:54:58.850 --> 00:55:00.770
But we have to be-- we have

00:55:00.770 --> 00:55:04.150
to have a fundamental
empathy with each other.

00:55:04.150 --> 00:55:07.050
And I think the most empathetic
man who ever held the presidency

00:55:07.050 --> 00:55:11.300
of the United States is
George Herbert Walker Bush.

00:55:11.300 --> 00:55:15.370
And I want to read you
quickly a letter that is--

00:55:15.370 --> 00:55:18.270
it's from another
planet basically.

00:55:18.270 --> 00:55:21.280
But, this is the kind of
person who was elected

00:55:21.280 --> 00:55:24.960
to the presidency 30
years ago this year.

00:55:24.960 --> 00:55:27.210
This is a letter that
President Bush wrote

00:55:27.210 --> 00:55:30.700
to his mother in the late 1950s.

00:55:30.700 --> 00:55:34.760
After the loss of the Bush's
daughter Robin to leukemia

00:55:34.760 --> 00:55:40.210
in the-- in 1953, they
had the four boys, Doro,

00:55:40.210 --> 00:55:42.110
their last child had
not yet been born,

00:55:42.110 --> 00:55:44.360
she would be born in '59.

00:55:44.360 --> 00:55:50.480
And this is the voice of
a son writing his mother

00:55:50.480 --> 00:55:52.910
about the loss of
his own daughter.

00:55:52.910 --> 00:55:56.900
And I share it with you
not least because it is

00:55:56.900 --> 00:55:59.940
of its unique in the
literature of the presidency,

00:55:59.940 --> 00:56:04.980
but I often think that if
I could be 5% of the man

00:56:04.980 --> 00:56:07.860
who wrote this letter,
I'd be ahead of the game.

00:56:07.860 --> 00:56:13.590
So this is the voice
of George H.W. Bush.

00:56:13.590 --> 00:56:16.750
"There is about our
house a need,

00:56:16.750 --> 00:56:18.590
the running pulsating
restlessness

00:56:18.590 --> 00:56:21.860
of the boys needs a counterpart.

00:56:21.860 --> 00:56:24.330
We need some starch
Chris frocks to go

00:56:24.330 --> 00:56:27.830
with all our torn neat
blue jeans and helmets.

00:56:27.830 --> 00:56:32.480
We need some soft blond hair
to offset those crew cuts.

00:56:32.480 --> 00:56:35.390
We need a dollhouse to
stand firm against our forts

00:56:35.390 --> 00:56:38.650
and rackets and thousand
baseball cards.

00:56:38.650 --> 00:56:41.970
We need a legitimate
Christmas angel,

00:56:41.970 --> 00:56:45.790
one who doesn't have
cuffs beneath the dress.

00:56:45.790 --> 00:56:49.490
We need someone who's
afraid of frogs.

00:56:49.490 --> 00:56:53.140
We need someone to cry
when I get mad not argue.

00:56:53.140 --> 00:56:55.480
We need a little
one who can kiss

00:56:55.480 --> 00:56:59.190
without leaving egg
or Jam or gum.

00:56:59.190 --> 00:57:00.980
We need a girl.

00:57:00.980 --> 00:57:04.270
We had one once, she'd
fight and cry and play

00:57:04.270 --> 00:57:07.440
and make her way just like
all the rest, but there was

00:57:07.440 --> 00:57:11.630
about her a certain
softness, she was patient.

00:57:11.630 --> 00:57:15.050
Her hugs were just a
little less wiggly.

00:57:15.050 --> 00:57:18.190
She'd stand beside our bed
until I felt her there,

00:57:18.190 --> 00:57:19.770
silently and comfortable.

00:57:19.770 --> 00:57:21.940
She'd put those precious
fragrant locks

00:57:21.940 --> 00:57:25.210
against my chest
and fall asleep.

00:57:25.210 --> 00:57:29.340
Her peace made me feel
strong and so very important,

00:57:29.340 --> 00:57:35.340
my daddy had a caress,
a certain ownership mode

00:57:35.340 --> 00:57:41.560
that I loved even more than the
'hi dad' that means so much.

00:57:41.560 --> 00:57:47.060
But she is still with us, we
need her and yet we have her.

00:57:47.060 --> 00:57:50.300
We can't touch her and
yet we can feel her."

00:57:50.300 --> 00:57:54.190
In the course of writing the
book about the president,

00:57:54.190 --> 00:57:57.790
I asked him to read that
letter aloud to me and we were

00:57:57.790 --> 00:58:01.030
in his office in Houston,
and long before he finished,

00:58:01.030 --> 00:58:05.100
he broke down an extraordinary
level of physical sobbing.

00:58:05.100 --> 00:58:07.600
So much so that his chief
of staff came in the office

00:58:07.600 --> 00:58:09.700
and looked and saw what we
were doing and said, why did--

00:58:09.700 --> 00:58:12.080
she asked me, she said, why
did you want President Bush

00:58:12.080 --> 00:58:13.940
to read that?

00:58:13.940 --> 00:58:17.950
And I said, well, if you want
to know someone's heart--

00:58:17.950 --> 00:58:22.580
and before I could finish, the
president jumped in and said,

00:58:22.580 --> 00:58:26.240
you have to know what breaks it.

00:58:28.250 --> 00:58:32.010
That's the best part
of the soul of America.

00:58:32.010 --> 00:58:33.810
Thank you.

00:58:33.810 --> 00:59:14.300
[ Applause ]

00:59:14.300 --> 00:59:17.340
&gt;&gt; Carla Hayden: You
could have kept clapping.

00:59:17.340 --> 00:59:20.840
I just wanted to say,
thank you Jon Meacham.

00:59:20.840 --> 00:59:25.290
You were the perfect person
to close the main stage today.

00:59:25.290 --> 00:59:26.900
You are what we needed.

00:59:26.900 --> 00:59:29.960
And I want to also
bring up another person,

00:59:29.960 --> 00:59:33.510
Mr. David Rubenstein, who is--

00:59:33.510 --> 00:59:43.480
[ Applause ]

00:59:43.480 --> 00:59:48.810
-- the person who brings
this festival to us,

00:59:48.810 --> 00:59:51.630
who is the major sponsor
who believes in literacy

00:59:51.630 --> 00:59:53.990
and learning and
the power of words.

00:59:53.990 --> 00:59:55.380
Thank you both.

00:59:55.380 --> 00:59:58.510
We appreciate you so much.

00:59:58.510 --> 01:00:05.210
[ Applause ]

01:00:05.210 --> 01:00:11.020
And I feel like we should just
keep clapping and standing.

01:00:11.020 --> 01:00:14.000
I want to thank all of you
for your patience today.

01:00:14.000 --> 01:00:17.890
I know there were long lines
for the signings and everything,

01:00:17.890 --> 01:00:20.500
but we can't thank you
enough for making this one

01:00:20.500 --> 01:00:21.800
of the premier events.

01:00:21.800 --> 01:00:30.010
And I have just news in that the
next date for next year will be

01:00:30.010 --> 01:00:33.640
on Saturday, August 31st,
Labor Day weekend again.

01:00:33.640 --> 01:00:38.210
We just got the confirmation, so
thank you all and keep reading.

